  where Gray(i) = i ^ (i >> 1).
  Proof: The loop for k in [0, p) sets mask = -(Gray(i0) & 1), then X ^= (mask & v[k]), then Gray(i0) >>= 1.
  This matches original code but with 'p' precomputed. Using p instead of repeated __ffs(stride)-1 does not change
  semantics because p is invariant w.r.t. the loop body and block configuration (stride is invariant within the kernel).

Invariant I2 (for the stride-walk loop at iteration i):
  Just before writing d_output[i], X equals the integer representation of the Sobol value for index i,
  and the update rule X ^= v[p-1] ^ v[__ffs(~((i - stride) | (stride - 1))) - 1] transitions from index (i - stride) to i.
  Proof: Same recurrence as the original code; we have only hoisted invariant quantities
  (p = __ffs(stride)-1, v_stridemask = stride-1, v[p-1]) into registers. The step uses i_prev = i - stride
  and applies the XOR rule identically to the original. Therefore I2 remains unbroken.

Termination and postcondition:
- For i0 < n_vectors, d_output[i0] is written with X * 2^-32, matching original computation.
- For i in [i0 + stride, n_vectors) stepping by stride, X is updated using the identical XOR rule and stored.
- Values remain in [0,1). No additional side effects are introduced.
*/

__launch_bounds__(256)
__global__
void sobolGPU_kernel(unsigned n_vectors, unsigned n_dimensions,
                     unsigned *__restrict__ d_directions,
                     float *__restrict__ d_output)
{
